---

# Introduction

ISO 22301 is more than a collection of business continuity requirements.

It is a **management system standard**, meaning it provides a structured framework that organizations use to establish, implement, maintain, and continually improve Business Continuity Management.

Like ISO 27001, ISO 9001, ISO 14001, and ISO 45001, ISO 22301 follows the **Annex SL High-Level Structure (HLS)**. This common structure allows organizations to integrate multiple management systems more easily, reducing duplication of policies, procedures, audits, and governance activities.

---

# What is a Management System?

A management system is a structured framework that enables an organization to achieve specific objectives through defined policies, processes, governance, and continual improvement.

For ISO 22301, the management system focuses on ensuring that:

- Critical business activities continue during disruptions.
- Recovery activities are coordinated.
- Responsibilities are clearly defined.
- Performance is monitored.
- The BCMS improves over time.

The emphasis is on managing business continuity systematically rather than reacting to emergencies on an ad hoc basis.

---

# Annex SL – The Common ISO Structure

Annex SL provides a standardized structure for modern ISO management system standards.

Organizations implementing multiple standards benefit because they share the same core clauses.

Examples include:

| Standard | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| ISO 9001 | Quality Management |
| ISO 14001 | Environmental Management |
| ISO 22301 | Business Continuity Management |
| ISO 27001 | Information Security Management |
| ISO 45001 | Occupational Health and Safety |
| ISO 42001 | Artificial Intelligence Management |

This common framework simplifies integrated management systems (IMS).

---

# Structure of ISO 22301

ISO 22301 contains ten clauses.

The first three clauses provide introductory information, while Clauses 4 through 10 contain the requirements for implementing and maintaining a BCMS.

| Clause | Title | Purpose |
|---------|-------|---------|
| 1 | Scope | Defines the purpose and applicability of the standard |
| 2 | Normative References | Lists referenced standards |
| 3 | Terms and Definitions | Defines important terminology |
| 4 | Context of the Organization | Understand the organization and define the BCMS scope |
| 5 | Leadership | Leadership commitment, policy, and governance |
| 6 | Planning | Risks, opportunities, objectives, and planning |
| 7 | Support | Resources, competence, awareness, communication, documented information |
| 8 | Operation | Business continuity planning, BIA, risk assessment, continuity strategies, plans, exercises |
| 9 | Performance Evaluation | Monitoring, measurement, internal audit, management review |
| 10 | Improvement | Corrective actions and continual improvement |

The first three clauses explain **what the standard is**, while Clauses 4–10 explain **how to implement and operate a BCMS**.

---

# Clauses 1–3: Foundation

These clauses establish the context for the standard.

### Clause 1 – Scope

Explains:

- Purpose of ISO 22301.
- Organizations that can apply it.
- General objectives.

The standard applies to organizations of any size or sector.

---

### Clause 2 – Normative References

Lists any documents that are considered indispensable for applying the standard.

For ISO 22301, this clause contains very limited normative references.

---

### Clause 3 – Terms and Definitions

Provides standardized terminology.

Examples include:

- Business Continuity
- Business Continuity Management System
- Incident
- Disruption
- Recovery
- Interested Party

Using common definitions improves consistency across organizations and audits.

---

# Clauses 4–10: The BCMS Requirements

The remainder of the standard specifies the requirements for implementing and maintaining an effective Business Continuity Management System.

These clauses align directly with the PDCA (Plan-Do-Check-Act) model and provide a structured roadmap for business continuity management.

---

# Mapping Clauses to the PDCA Cycle

The ISO 22301 requirements can be grouped according to the PDCA model.

| PDCA Phase | ISO 22301 Clauses |
|------------|-------------------|
| **Plan** | Clauses 4, 5, 6, and part of Clause 7 |
| **Do** | Clause 8 and operational aspects of Clause 7 |
| **Check** | Clause 9 |
| **Act** | Clause 10 |

This structure ensures that organizations continuously improve their BCMS rather than treating it as a one-time implementation project.

---

# Why the Clause Structure Matters

Understanding the clause structure helps organizations:

- Plan implementation activities.
- Conduct internal audits.
- Prepare for certification audits.
- Assign responsibilities.
- Develop documentation.
- Integrate ISO 22301 with other management systems.

For Lead Implementers and Lead Auditors, familiarity with the clause structure is essential because certification audits are performed against these requirements.

